      "rationale": "Three-mesh GCI study conducted on pre-revision geometry; GCI for NIH is 7.2% on the fine mesh, exceeding the 5% target. Post-revision geometry mesh study not repeated. Achieved level 2 against required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, outlet pressure, fluid temperature, hematocrit) documented with measurement uncertainty and matched to simulation inputs within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Four of five boundary condition parameters documented with calibrated uncertainty; hematocrit variability between test runs not formally propagated into simulation boundary conditions. Achieved level 3 against required level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g. E_rel or validation uncertainty U_val) computed for hemolysis QoI across all operating points; comparison includes combined simulation and experimental uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Relative error computed at all five operating points; combined uncertainty interval constructed using Monte Carlo UQ for simulation and reported experimental repeatability. Comparison metric meets level 3 criteria but does not include model-form uncertainty contribution required for level 4. Achieved level 3 against required level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation QoI (NIH) directly maps to the clinical decision threshold; scalar hemolysis model demonstrated to capture dominant damage mechanisms across the VAD operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "NIH is the clinical QoI and is directly predicted by the power-law hemolysis scalar. Sensitivity analysis shows NIH is dominated by high-shear impeller-blade passages; however, relevance of the scalar model under off-design recirculation conditions is not established. Achieved level 3 against required level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
